metadata.name: operation 04 #24
metadata.description:
The final extrapolation of the operation Voronoi series. Multiple walk sequences are added, as is another drawing method, for increased variety. Five traits describe each mint: 

Color: Ten different named color palettes, with "Monochrome" the rarest.

Arcs: The number of elements drawn, with 100 the rarest.

Resolution: The X/Y resolution of Voronoi nodes, with 2 the rarest.

Pattern: The walk style, with "Static" being the rarest.

Shape: The drawing element, either ellipse or, someone less likely, rectangle.

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: operation 03 #12
metadata.description:
The third of four operations, this further extrapolates the algorithm. Per-view randomization is in the speed and size of the drawing of the rays, and in the placement of the Voronoi points. Each viewing is unique, but each mint is also unique.

The image draws in its entirety in about 10 seconds. After 20 seconds, it clears, randomizes the placement, and draws again. Full-screen capable.

Three traits describe each individual mint:

Color: There are nine different color palettes, with "Leaves" being a 20% likelihood, and all the others 10% likelihood.

Arc: This is the number of elements drawn around each point. There are three possible states, with 50 being a 10% likelihood, 250 being a 20% likelihood, and 100 being the default at 70%.

Resolution: This is the number of points in the Voronoi field. There are four candidates, with 1 being the least likely (10%), 2 and 3 having a 20% likelihood of occurring, and 4 being the most common at 50%.

Created in p5.js

metadata.name: Ries #356
metadata.description:
Ries is 500 sheets of paper. 
Ries is an cut-up text-artwork.
Ries is artwork generated by an algorithm based on seeded random numbers.
Ries is a digital artwork installed in 5 forms in exhibitions setting.
Ries is an NFT artwork. 

Ries is an artwork where I try bring together my experience of doing gallery exhibitions, my love for generative and copy machine art, DIY-punk aesthetics, NFT’s and chaos. 

The edition of Ries will be installed in different forms and collages in a gallery exhibition in Walden Kunstaustellungen in Berlin in July of 2022. Opening is at 8.7. 19.00, welcome if you are in Berlin.
/www.galerie-walden.de/

The seed idea for the project was the method of cut-up where a text (or something else) is cut into pieces and then rearranged to form something new. A modified Markov’s Chain algorithm makes a small text or a group of words from a pool of texts that include Art texts about cut up technique and generative art talk from tweets. These words form a visual bottom layer and then another layer of words samples the first, cutting it up and thus following the theme of the artwork.

Since the single iterations of the project are designed to be used in a collage, they come in various tone, density, detail and scale. One can test from the variations button and get a sense of what the generator produces. 

Controls in live view:
-Pressing  j exports the current image as jpeg
-Pressing  p  exports the current image as png

To change the detail level one can access the pixel density of render by adding ?pixDens=4 to the end of the URL in live view. You can of course you any number other than 4 also. I it renders just a black image, you have to lower the number, since it is then too large for WEBGL to render.

Designed to be best rendered on desktop Chrome.

Pricing info
22 tez - Includes a gallery shown, signed print sent to minter by mail or by telefax(!)
11 tez - A fair price for an artwork, also the minter can personally pick up a signed gallery shown print from the gallery, after the exhibition.
5 tez - 1/2 fair price
2 tez - bottom dollar

If you minted on lower tiers and would want a print, please contact the artist per twitter dm to “upgrade”. If you bought secondary, and would want a print, please contact the artist per twitter dm.

Features exist mostly to help with artwork pairing for the collectors.


Markov’s chain code core is based on Markov Me! By https://codepen.io/alexkramerbanjo , MIT License

Displacement shader based on the wonderful shader examples by Adam Ferris


The artist holds the right to use the whole edition of Ries for display purposes for future exhibitions without asking permission or notifying the owners of the NFT’s.

1.7.2022 in Berlin
Antti Pussinen

www.anttipussinen.net
www.twitter.com/antti_pussinen

metadata.name: Asta Collection #37
metadata.description:
In the creation of "Asta," a tapestry of mathematical precision and mythological grandeur unfolds before the viewer. The name itself is an ode to the Old Norse term "Ástríðr," which combines "ás," or the divine, with "fríðr," the beautiful. Much like the gods and goddesses of Norse mythology, "Asta" dwells in a space where disparate forces like unity and fragmentation or chaos and order find harmony.

The visual core of the artwork is composed of concentric circles meticulously shaped from individual spheres. Each circle, akin to the realms over which Norse gods presided, is a universe unto itself, yet all function as part of an overarching cosmic design. The deities of Norse lore were complex beings, embodying both virtues and flaws, and such dualities reverberate through each sphere and orbit within the piece.

Serving as a backdrop for this celestial assembly is a canvas marked by signs of distress and decay. This reflects the concept of entropy inherent in Norse cosmology—often symbolized by the serpent Jormungandr biting its own tail to form a circle. Circles that appear to have lost their center drift aimlessly, reminiscent of gods who have fallen from grace, thereby capturing the unpredictable and imperfect nature of existence.

"Asta" is not merely a visual spectacle; it's an invitation to embark on a philosophical exploration. As viewers traverse the delicate balance between intricate patterns and intentional anomalies, they are compelled to confront the eternal dualities symbolized in Norse mythology—such as order and chaos, the finite and the infinite, and the divine and the mortal.

For those who engage with it, "Asta" serves as more than just an art piece. It becomes a poetic meeting with the sublime and a tribute to the complexities that both life and mythology bestow upon the human experience.

Controls
========
The controls are as follows:
- Press `t` - 370 x 200 png output (thumbnail)
- Press `1` - 650 x 1200 png output
- Press `2` - 1300 x 2400 png output
- Press `3` - 1950 x 3600 png output
- Press `4` - 3250 x 6000 png output
- Press `5` - 5200 x 9600 png output
- Press `6` - 7800 x 14400 png output

Please note that the larger the output, the longer it will take to generate.

metadata.name: EYES #141
metadata.description:
The beauty and soul of eyes have always fascinated me. There are billions of eyes in the world, all with different colors, textures and shapes and each one is still unique. With this project, I wanted to capture that natural beauty of the eyes, but also give them my unique colorful style.

Zombie and Cat eyes are more rare. Who will collect the Zombie Cat eye?

----

Created with the help of amazing cables.gl. For optimization purposes, in order to make the project load properly on fxhash, I had to use 2 textures for the eye pupil shapes instead of procedurally generating them. There is also hdr map loaded for the reflections.  

Press E to download the generated image.

----

All who collected NEBULAE were added to the reserve list. <3
